&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="lnt"&gt;10
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class="lntd"&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-yaml" data-lang="yaml"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="nn"&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;load_validation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;- &lt;span class="nt"&gt;type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="l"&gt;throw_if_empty&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;sql&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="l"&gt;validate_data_not_empty&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;msg&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;&amp;#39;No data extracted for the given date!&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;active&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="kc"&gt;false&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;- &lt;span class="nt"&gt;type&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="l"&gt;throw_if_not_empty&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;sql&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="l"&gt;validate_data_duplicates&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nt"&gt;msg&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s1"&gt;&amp;#39;Duplicate data detected!&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nn"&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For every object in the &lt;code&gt;[step]_validation&lt;/code&gt; the &lt;code&gt;sql&lt;/code&gt; is executed in the &lt;code&gt;[step]_con&lt;/code&gt; connection, and it can either throw error message defined in &lt;code&gt;msg&lt;/code&gt; or not if the condition (&lt;code&gt;type:throw_if_empty | type:throw_if_not_empty&lt;/code&gt; or) is met or not.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Query Documentation</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/query-doc/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/query-doc/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="query-documentation"&gt;Query Documentation&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In some ETL processes, particularly during the &lt;strong&gt;Transform&lt;/strong&gt; step, queries may become too complex to manage as a single string. To address this, the configuration supports a structured approach where you can break down a query into individual fields and their respective SQL components. This approach improves modularity, readability, and maintainability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h4 id="structure"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A complex query is defined as a top-level heading (e.g., &lt;code&gt;# My Complex Query&lt;/code&gt;) in the configuration. Each field included in the query is represented as a Level 2 heading (e.g., &lt;code&gt;## Field Name&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Data Quality</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/data-quality/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/data-quality/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="data-quality"&gt;Data Quality&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;DATA_QUALITY&lt;/code&gt; section allows you to define and execute validation rules to ensure the quality of your data. Each rule performs a check using a SQL query to identify records that violate a specific condition. Optionally, you can define a query to fix any identified issues automatically if applicable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;h4 id="data-quality-structure"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Data Quality Structure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Metadata&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;code&gt;DATA_QUALITY&lt;/code&gt; section contains metadata describing its purpose and activation status.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Validation Rules&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Each validation rule is defined as a Level 2 heading under the &lt;code&gt;DATA_QUALITY&lt;/code&gt; block.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Rules include a query to check for violations and, optionally, a query to fix issues.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Execution&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Exports</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/exports/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/exports/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="exports"&gt;Exports&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;EXPORTS&lt;/code&gt; section in the ETL configuration handles exporting data to files. This is particularly useful for generating reports for internal departments, regulators, partners, or saving processed data to a data lake. By leveraging DuckDB&amp;rsquo;s ability to export data in various formats, this section supports file generation with flexibility and precision.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for full examples including CSV, Excel, and template-based exports.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Scripts</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/scripts/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/scripts/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="scripts"&gt;Scripts&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;SCRIPTS&lt;/strong&gt; section allows you to &lt;strong&gt;execute SQL queries&lt;/strong&gt; that &lt;strong&gt;donâ€™t fit into other predefined sections&lt;/strong&gt; (ETL, EXPORTS, etc.).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id="-when-to-use-scripts"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ðŸ”¹ When to Use SCRIPTS?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;âœ… &lt;strong&gt;Running cleanup queries after an ETL job&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
âœ… &lt;strong&gt;Executing ad-hoc maintenance tasks&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
âœ… &lt;strong&gt;Running SQL commands that donâ€™t need to return results&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
âœ… &lt;strong&gt;Executing SQL scripts for database optimizations&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for full markdown examples and behavior.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Multi-Queries</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/multi-queries/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/multi-queries/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="multi-queries"&gt;Multi-Queries&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;MULTI_QUERIES&lt;/code&gt; section allows you to define multiple queries with similar structures and aggregate their results using a SQL &lt;code&gt;UNION&lt;/code&gt;. This is particularly useful when generating summaries or reports that combine data from multiple queries into a single result set.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for full examples and execution flow.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Logs</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/logs/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/logs/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="logs-handling--logs"&gt;Logs Handling (&lt;code&gt;# LOGS&lt;/code&gt;)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ETLX provides a &lt;strong&gt;logging mechanism&lt;/strong&gt; that allows &lt;strong&gt;saving logs&lt;/strong&gt; into a database. This is useful for tracking &lt;strong&gt;executions, debugging, and auditing ETL processes&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for example configurations like &lt;code&gt;AUTO_LOGS&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;create_missing_columns&lt;/code&gt; dynamic helper.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Loading Config Dependencies</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/requires/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/requires/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="requires"&gt;REQUIRES&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;REQUIRES&lt;/code&gt; section in the ETL configuration allows you to load dependencies from external Markdown configurations. These dependencies can either be loaded from file paths or dynamically through queries. This feature promotes modularity and reusability by enabling you to define reusable parts of the configuration in separate files or queries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for full examples showing loading from queries and files.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Actions</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/actions/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/actions/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="actions"&gt;ACTIONS&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are scenarios in ETL workflows where actions such as downloading, uploading, compressing or copying files cannot be performed using SQL alone. The &lt;code&gt;ACTIONS&lt;/code&gt; section allows you to define steps for copying or transferring files using the file system or external protocols.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for the full list of supported action types and examples.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Notify</title><link>https://example.org/configuration/notify/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://example.org/configuration/notify/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="notify"&gt;NOTIFY&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;NOTIFY&lt;/code&gt; section enables sending notifications (e.g., email via SMTP) with dynamic templates populated from SQL query results. This is useful for monitoring ETL processes and sending status reports.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(See README for full markdown example including template and data_sql examples.)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>